flowRoot.flowPara: And say gentoo stable is at 1.5.5 on 03/23/09.
Then the lag is 3/23/09-2/27/09, the time between now and the oldest new release.

One of the tough challenges of the lag based analysis is understanding exactly which versions obsolete others. The original method ignored version numbers and always assumed the last release was the latest and, therefore, best. However, this is not always the case. Many of core projects that other projects depend upon maintain multiple branches of software. This is common practice in order to keep a compatible version up-to-date while developing a new incompatible version. For example, Python, an interpretted programming language, releases both 2.x versions and 3.x versions. The original analysis would then obsolete a 3.x version if a new 2.x release occurred. This is not ideal, however, because 3.x is better than 2.x in terms of features. So, only other 3.x versions should obsolete the existing 3.x.

To solve this problem of understanding versions, a notion of a version tree has been created. It works by splitting a version string into signficant tokens which are then order by significance. For example, 3.0 becomes 3 and 0 with the 3 being more important. From these series of tokens a tree is built with an empty root and the most signficant tokens at depth 1 and the least significant tokens as leaves. Each level is then sorted by release date. Therefore, we get a tree in that anything to the right of a particular version traversal obsoletes the version.

An example version tree is at the right. It shows the resulting tree for some versions of Python. The blue nodes have corresponding dates which are the release date for the version created by traversing to it from the root of the tree.

Much of the analysis is centered around a notion of freshness. This is a metric which defines how obsolete a particular software component of a larger compilation is with respect to the independent development. For any moment in time a component is as fresh as the time between now and the oldest new release. New releases are those that obsolete the current version.

This metric provides a concrete way of comparing the state of single components in a compilation and comparing the state of groups of components. Once this metric is used to identify particular components or compilations that succeed in minimizing this value, further work can be done to understand why this value is low.

One technique for analyzing the data is purely comparing Linux distributions against each other. This comparison serves two roles. The first is tagent to the research, it identifies which distro is generally freshest and is useful in selecting a distributions for use. Second, it allows one to identify the interesting cases amongst distributions. From that point, closer analysis can be done to determine the differing factors between them. In the graph below we see 8 of the 9 distributions whose data is collected. Although overwhelming, this graph concretely shows many trends between distros that have only been anecdotely known previously.

One of the things found in this freshness graph is the effects of a distributions release cycle. As seen below, Gentoo, a rolling release distribution, maintains a much closer relationship with upstream when compared to Ubuntu, a fixed 6-month release cycle. This comparison can then be generalized to the greater argument for continuous integration of software components versus staged development and integration.

flowRoot.flowPara: With time, the amount of data collected increases. This is the largest source for improvement. In addition to collecting more data of the existing projects, more project sources will be added into the database. Also, more data normalization will be done which will, in turn, create a larger base for analysis.

At this point, much of the work is just beginning. Over time, more work will be done on both analyzing the data and providing the data to the community at large. Hopefully, these two approaches will both provide the tools necessary for developers to optimize their development practices and allow others to analyze the larger trends looking for further improvements.
